yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guernsey]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Isle of Man]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.je/health/coronavirus/Pages/index.aspx Official website]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Jersey]]\n[[Category:2020 in Jersey|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Jersey]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Crown dependencies|Jersey]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|cases in the British Crown dependency|the U.S. state|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Jersey}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Jersey}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jersey\n| map1 = \n| places = \n| legend1 =\n| map2 = \n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Jersey]]\n| first_case = Imported from Italy\n| arrival_date = 10 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=10|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 278<ref name=\"govjjcases\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/Health/Coronavirus/Pages/CoronavirusCases.aspx|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases|website=www.gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref name=\"channelislands\">{{cite news |title=Live updates: Number of Coronavirus cases in the Channel Islands |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-12/live-updates-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-the-channel-islands/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=itv.com |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries</ref>\n| recovery_cases = 165<ref name=\"govjjcases\"/>\n| deaths = 19<ref name=\"govjjcases\"/>\n| website = {{url|https://www.gov.je/coronavirus}}\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Bailiwick of Jersey''' is part of an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first case in [[Bailiwick of Jersey|Jersey]] was confirmed on 10 March 2020 when a person tested positive on the island after returning from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]].\n\nThe Government of Jersey's strategy has been to delay the spread of the virus, avoid vulnerable people from catching it, help the island's health service cope with the number of people requiring hospital care and to save as many lives as possible.<ref name=\"ceo\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/StatementfromCE.aspx|title=Statement from Chief Executive, Charlie Parker|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15|date=15 April 2020}}</ref> It acknowledged that many islanders would become infected, and has sought to ensure that the best possible medical care is available to them.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nA new coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) was first identified in Wuhan, Hubei, China, in late December 2019 as the cause of a cluster of cases of an acute respiratory disease now referred to as coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/china/news/detail/09-01-2020-who-statement-regarding-cluster-of-pneumonia-cases-in-wuhan-china |title=WHO Statement Regarding Cluster of Pneumonia Cases in Wuhan, China |publisher=WHO |date=31 December 2019 |accessdate=12 March 2020 }}</ref> As of 31 March 2020 more than 190 countries and territories have been affected, with major outbreaks in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]].<ref name=\"WOM\">{{cite web |url= https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Update (Live) |work=Worldometer |year=2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by Johns Hopkins CSSE|last=|first=|date=|website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> On March 11, 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) characterised the spread of COVID-19 as a [[pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 - 11 March 2020 |publisher=WHO |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51839944|title=Coronavirus confirmed as pandemic|date=2020-03-11|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Bailiwick of Jersey medical cases chart}}\n* On 30 January the Government of Jersey made its first announcement about the virus, saying that its cross-Government review group met that morning to discuss the situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/pages/CoronavirusAdvice.aspx|title=Advice is issued on Novel Coronavirus|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n* On 31 January the Government issued travel advice for islanders returning from affected areas of China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/CoronavirusUpdate2.aspx|title=Coronavirus: travel advice|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n*On 10 March, the first case was confirmed. The infected person had travelled from Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/10/breaking-first-coronavirus-case-in-jersey-confirmed/|title=First coronavirus case in Jersey confirmed|last=Maguire|first=Jack|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> \n*On 11 March a second case was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-11/coronavirus-second-case-confirmed-in-jersey/|title=Coronavirus: Second case confirmed in Jersey|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 20 March there were 10 cases confirmed in Jersey, two of which were believed to have been contracted within the island.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.je/Health/Coronavirus/Pages/CoronavirusCases.aspx|title=Number of coronavirus (COVID-19) tests and confirmed cases in Jersey|website=Government of Jersey|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/20/coronavirus-hospital-visits-stopped-two-patients-treated-for-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus: Hospital visits stopped, two patients treated for COVID-19|website=Jersey Evening Post|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 25 March a person in their 80's died. They had long-term health conditions and had been receiving palliative care before contracting COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/26/breaking-jersey-suffers-first-coronavirus-death/|title=Jersey suffers first coronavirus death|last=Heath|first=Richard|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*On 29 March a second person died. They were in their 70's and had long-term health conditions before contracting the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-29/second-person-dies-of-coronavirus-in-jersey/|title=Second person dies in Jersey after contracting Coronavirus|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*On 30 March, the Chief Minister stated that there were ten patients with COVID-19 being treated at the hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/watch-5000-tests-their-way-jersey-and-10-hospital/|title=WATCH: 5,000 test kits on their way to Jersey|last=Express|first=Bailiwick|website=Bailiwick Express|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*On 2 April, nine patients were being treated in hospital.\n*On 4 April, a third death was announced - a patient in their late 60s who had underlying health conditions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/04/04/third-coronavirus-death-in-jersey/|title=Third coronavirus death in Jersey|last=Stephenson|first=Lucy|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> and the total number of cases confirmed stood at 126.<ref name=\"channelislands\"/>\n* On 6 April, the number of confirmed cases totalled 169.<ref name=\"channelislands\"/> 19 patients at the hospital were being treated for COVID-19.\n* On 14 April the number of people that have died either under the care of Health & Community Services or in the community where the death certificate mentions COVID-19 increased to six.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/Covid-19Recording.aspx|title=Recording of deaths from COVID-19|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* On 15 April, Charlie Parker, Chief Executive of the Government of Jersey, stated that there were 21 patients with COVID-19 being treated at the Jersey General Hospital and eight others elsewhere in other hospital settings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-04-15/some-degree-of-confidentiality-needed-in-terms-of-positive-cases-says-charlie-parker/|title='Some degree of confidentiality' needed in terms of positive cases, says Charlie Parker|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* On 20 April, 118 cases, almost 50% of confirmed cases, were now classified as recovered. In hospital there were 63 patients of which 14 were Covid-19 positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/half-islanders-diagnosed-corona-virus-fully-recovered/#.Xp4PMhSArlI|title=Half of islanders officially diagnosed with covid-19 'fully recovered'|website=Bailiwick Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Response by the Government of Jersey==\n===Overview of response===\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\nOn 12 March, the advice from [[John Le Fondr\u00e9 Jr|Senator John Fondr\u00e9]], [[Chief Minister of Jersey]] was to maintain a semblance of normal life, including continuing to go on holidays off-island,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/12/coronavirus-keep-calm-and-carry-on-advice-from-jerseys-government/|title=Coronavirus: 'Keep calm and carry on' advice from Jersey's government|last=Stephenson|first=Lucy|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> but by 14 March his advice changed, requesting over-65s to start [[social distancing]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-14/coronavirus-social-distancing-guidelines-issued-amongst-new-government-advice-in-jersey/|title=Coronavirus: All islanders over 65 should start social distancing says Jersey Government|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and on 20 March he extended this advice to islanders of all ages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-20/jersey-s-chief-minister-all-islanders-to-practice-social-distancing/|title=Jersey's Chief Minister: All islanders to practice social distancing|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Islanders must avoid non-essential travel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/14/new-measures-announced-to-combat-coronavirus/|title=New measures announced to combat coronavirus|last=Maguire|first=Jack|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\"travel\" />\n\nOn 19 February a helpline was set up to answer islanders' questions about Coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/pages/CoronavirusHelplineLaunched.aspx|title=Coronavirus helpline launched|date=19 February 2020|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> It is manned by staff from Customer & Local Services, Health and Community Services and [[Environmental health officer|Environmental Health]]. It handles on average 550 calls per day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/CoronavirusHelpline.aspx|title=Coronavirus helpline update|date=9 April 2020|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nFrom 20 March all travellers arriving on the island, other than essential workers, must [[Isolation_(health_care)#Self-isolation|self-isolate]] for 14 days.<ref name=\"travel\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-20/all-travellers-to-jersey-must-self-isolate-for-14-days/|title=All travellers to Jersey must self isolate for 14 days|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> From midnight on 26 March those aged over 65 and people with certain underlying medical conditions must self-isolate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/ShieldOver65.aspx|title=Health Minister announces new measures for people aged over 65|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> On 28 March, islanders were told that if one or more people in a household develop COVID-19 symptoms then all the other members of the household must also self-isolate for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/28/entire-households-now-being-told-to-isolate-if-a-member-has-coronavirus-symptoms/|title=Entire households now being told to isolate if a member has coronavirus symptoms|last=Heath|first=Richard|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March the Chief Minister called for young people to heed the social distancing advice for the sake of their family members, and bemoaned the spread of unhelpful rumours by [[conspiracy theorists]] over social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/27/covid-19-waterfront-hotel-could-act-as-300-bed-field-hospital/|title=COVID-19: 'Young people vital in helping to slow the spread', says Chief Minister|last=Maguire|first=Jack|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 29 March, the Chief Minister announced a lockdown, effective from 8 am the following morning. Islanders must stay at home other than for short periods for specific purposes unless they are employed in an essential function.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/Health/Coronavirus/Pages/StayAtHome.aspx|title='Stay at Home': Advice for Islanders|website=gov.je|access-date=2020-03-29|date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe States Assembly passed new legislation, including a law to empower the police to remove people from public areas, enforce self-isolation, testing and screening, and detain those who are potentially infected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/04/01/police-dont-call-us-over-lockdown-breaches/|title=Police: Don't call us over lockdown breaches|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Chief Minister had said that antibody testing would be key to the ending of the lockdown with 10,000 kits arriving in Jersey in mid April, which were being tested, with a further 150,000 on order from a different supplier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/antibody-tests-key-unlocking-lockdown/#.Xp6hQxSArlI|title=Antibody tests \u2018key\u2019 to unlocking lockdown|website=www.bailiwickexpress.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21|date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nInformal Governmental discussions on a plan for removing restrictions began on mid April with the intention to enter formal discussions by the end of the month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/guernsey-phases-out-lockdown-jersey-talks-begin/#.Xp6fshSArlI|title=Guernsey: lockdown exit plan published. Jersey: formal talks begin|website=www.bailiwickexpress.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21|date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n===Testing===\n{{see also|COVID-19 testing}}\nInitially tests were sent to [[Colindale]] in London for processing,<ref name=\"muscat\">{{Cite video|title=Live: Update from Dr. Ivan Muscat, Medical Officer of Health|url=https://www.facebook.com/GovernmentofJersey/videos/226958598551762/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|via=Facebook Live}}</ref> with results taking between 48 hours and five days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/CoronavirusTestResultsLatest.aspx|title=32 test positive for COVID-19 to date\n|last=Jersey|first=States of|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> In March arrangements were being made to establish a test facility on island, and this was expected to be ready as soon as the end of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-24/jersey-could-have-coronavirus-testing-site-within-the-next-month/|title=Jersey could have Coronavirus testing site by end of April|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Five thousand test kits were been ordered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/watch-5000-tests-their-way-jersey-and-10-hospital/|title=WATCH: 5,000 test kits on their way to Jersey|last=Express|first=Bailiwick|website=Bailiwick Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March a testing centre was opened at Five Oaks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-15/coronavirus-testing-centre-opened-in-jersey/|title=Coronavirus testing centre opened in Jersey|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April the government announced that the 5,000 COVID-19 [[PCR test]]s that it had ordered were being supplied by [[Cepheid Inc]] in California and two other companies. 150,000 [[serology test]]s have been ordered from a UK supplier.<ref name=\"muscat\" /> The serology tests will identify antibodies in people who have developed immunity. They are due to arrive in batches with the first batch expected in April.<ref name=\"muscat\" /> They intend to test all households in order to enable a phased 'managed exit from the stay home restrictions'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/IslandwideTesting.aspx|title=Coronavirus testing update: Island-wide testing confirmed|date=2 April 2020|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Islanders will be asked to attend mobile testing centres around the island.<ref name=\"muscat\" />\n\nAs of 1:20pm on 4 April there had been 1,451 tests, of which 126 were confirmed positive and 209 are awaiting results.<ref name=\"tally\">{{cite web |title=Number of coronavirus (COVID-19) tests and confirmed cases in Jersey |url=https://www.gov.je/Health/Coronavirus/Pages/CoronavirusCases.aspx |website=gov.je |publisher=Government of Jersey |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Three people have died as a result of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/04/04/third-coronavirus-death-in-jersey/|title=Third coronavirus death in Jersey|last=Stephenson|first=Lucy|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nOn-island testing commenced on 8 April, with the intention that laboratory staff will work 24 hours a day, seven days a week to be able to process same-day results.<ref name=\"onisland\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel103.com/news/jersey-news/coronavirus-on-island-testing-begins/|title=Coronavirus: On-Island Testing Begins|website=Channel 103|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Pathology Manager said \"Around 20 biomedical scientists and laboratory support staff have been trained to perform [the tests].\"<ref name=\"onisland\" /> Initially the lab was processing 75 tests a day, increasing to 120 a day from 15 April.<ref name=\"ceo\" />\n\n===Financial support===\nOn 12 March, the Minister for Economic Development announced deferred social security and GST payments, and deferred rent for businesses where the government was the landlord.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/12/measures-to-protect-jersey-economy-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Measures to protect Jersey economy amid coronavirus outbreak|last=Stephenson|first=Lucy|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 20 March, he announced that government would pay a subsidy of up to \u00a3200 a week to workers in the hospitality, retail, wholesale and agriculture and fisheries industries until the end of April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-20/jersey-government-announces-economic-rescue-package-for-vulnerable-businesses/|title=Jersey's Government announces economic rescue package for vulnerable businesses|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> He announced an enhanced package of support on 26 March, using the island's strategic reserve - the so-called '[[rainy day fund]]' - to pay up to 80% of the wages of affected staff in certain industries, capped at \u00a31,600 a month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/27/biggest-economic-support-package-in-jerseys-history-announced-to-help-firms-through-coronavirus-outbreak/|title='Biggest economic support package in Jersey's history' announced to help firms through coronavirus outbreak|last=Heath|first=Ian|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nJersey has its own health service, separate to the [[NHS]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/Health/Travelling/Pages/MovingReturning.aspx|title=Health costs when moving or returning to live in Jersey|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Its Health & Community Services department has developed its own response to the virus.\n\nOn 19 March, the Minister for Health and Community Services announced that the [[Jersey General Hospital|General Hospital]] would be closed to visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-19/jersey-general-hospital-closes-to-visitors-over-coronavirus-cases/|title=Jersey General Hospital closes to visitors over Coronavirus cases|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March government announced that non-essential operations and outpatient appointments would be cancelled for a four-week period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-20/operations-and-outpatient-appointments-cancelled-at-jersey-s-hospital/|title=Operations and outpatient appointments cancelled at Jersey's hospital|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March the Chief Minister stated that ten patients were being cared for at the General Hospital,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-30/ten-of-jersey-s-positive-coronavirus-cases-are-in-hospital/|title=Ten of Jersey's positive Coronavirus cases are in hospital|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and that the island has 27 [[ventilators]]. The island does not have its own [[extracorporeal membrane oxygenation]] (ECMO) machine - patients needing one would normally be transferred to [[Southampton General Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/watch-key-health-questions-go-unanswered/|title=WATCH: Key health questions go unanswered|last=Express|first=Bailiwick|website=Bailiwick Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> People who have worked in the health sector such as dentists and pharmacists were asked to volunteer to support the health service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/HealthStaffCall.aspx|title=Call out for additional health staff|date=30 March 2020|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n17 residents at an unnamed [[care home]] are being treated for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/04/08/cluster-of-17-covid-19-cases-in-island-care-home-but-services-do-have-sufficient-protective-equipment-minister-says/|title=Cluster of 17 Covid-19 cases in Island care home \u2013 but services do have 'sufficient' protective equipment, minister says|last=Morris|first=Michael|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April the Government announced that a [[field hospital]] would be built on a playing field at Millbrook.<ref name=\"fh\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/TemporaryHospital.aspx|title=Jersey Nightingale hospital approved|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The so-called [[NHS Nightingale Hospitals|Nightingale hospital]] will cost \u00a314.4m and will take less than a month to build.<ref name=\"fh2\" /> It will be 150m long and 30m wide, containing six wards of 30 beds each,<ref name=\"fh\" /> but could be expanded to contain up to 240 beds.<ref name=\"fh2\" /> The field belongs to the family of [[Jesse Boot, 1st Baron Trent|Lord Trent]].<ref name=\"fh\" /> The contractor building the site, J3 Limited, is a joint venture between [[Sir Robert McAlpine]], Garenne Construction Group and FES Group. It was involved in building Nightingale hospitals in Glasgow and Manchester.<ref name=\"fh2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/ChiefMinisterFieldHospital.aspx|title=Chief Minister statement on field hospital|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nMilitary helicopters based at [[RNAS Culdrose]] in Cornwall are on standby to transport critically ill patients from Jersey to intensive care facilities at hospitals in the UK if necessary. They could also be used to fly in medicines, equipment and specialist doctors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/military-pilots-join-covid-19-helicopter-task-force/|title=Military pilots to fly critically ill island virus patients|last=Express|first=Bailiwick|website=Bailiwick Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n===Education and childcare===\nOn 18 March, it was announced that all schools and colleges would close for at least four weeks starting from 23 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.je/News/2020/Pages/schoolsclosure.aspx|title=Schools and colleges to close to students to reduce the spread of Covid-19|website=Government of Jersey|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPeople deemed to work in essential roles are able to apply for their children to attend school or child care so that they can continue to perform their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/pages/CriticalWorkersPhase.aspx|title=Second wave of critical workers announced|date=30 March 2020|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Closures and shutdowns===\nOn 17 March, [[Cineworld]] announced the closure of the only cinema on the island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-17/coronavirus-jersey-s-only-cinema-to-close-until-further-notice/|title=Coronavirus: Jersey's only cinema to close until further notice|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, ministers announced that pubs, bars and nightclubs should close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-22/coronavirus-bars-and-nightclubs-to-close-in-jersey/|title=Coronavirus: Bars and nightclubs to close in Jersey|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, government announced that its sports centres would close,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-23/coronavirus-jersey-sports-centres-to-close-from-today/|title=Coronavirus: Jersey sports centres to close from today|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and [[Jersey Zoo]] announced that it would be closed from 24 March until further notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-23/coronavirus-durrell-team-devestated-as-zoo-closes-until-further-notice/|title=Coronavirus: Durrell team 'devastated' as zoo closes until further notice|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\n\nOn 10 March the [[Lions Club]] announced that its Swimarathon, a charity fund raising swimming event due to have over 3,500 participants would not take place in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-10/coronavirus-jersey-s-swimarathon-cancelled/|title=Coronavirus: Jersey's swimarathon cancelled|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, organisers of the 75th [[Liberation Day (Channel Islands)|Liberation Day]] celebrations announced that they would be scaled back.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-18/coronavirus-liberation-75-celebrations-scaled-back/|title=Coronavirus: Jersey's Liberation 75 celebrations scaled back|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March the organisers of the [[Jersey Battle of Flowers]] announced that the event, which was next due to take place in August 2020, would be cancelled for the first time in 70 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-25/jersey-battle-of-flowers-cancelled/|title=Jersey Battle of Flowers cancelled|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March the organisers of the 2020 TMF Island Walk announced that the annual sponsored round-the-island walk due to take place on 20 June would be postponed until later in the summer or may not take place. The event usually attracts 1,500 walkers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://islandwalk.je/covid19|title=Charities|website=islandwalk.je|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Consumer response===\nIn late February, stocks of [[hand sanitiser]] were running low,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/02/28/coronavirus-hand-sanitiser-stocks-run-low/|title=Coronavirus: Hand sanitiser stocks run low|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and in early March, Jersey supermarkets reported unprecedented demand for certain items such as toilet roll. Some retailers introduced restrictions to prevent people from stockpiling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-11/bulk-buying-restricted-in-shops-in-bid-to-stop-panic-buying/|title=Bulk buying restricted in Channel Island shops in bid to stop panic buying|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Travel===\nOn 3 March, France and Germany were added to the list of countries from which travellers would need to self-isolate for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-03/france-added-to-list-of-affected-areas-in-guernsey-and-jersey-travel-advice/|title=France added to list of affected areas in Guernsey and Jersey travel advice|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, the airline [[Flybe]] which had been founded in Jersey and serviced the most air routes from the island went into administration, citing Coronavirus as part of the reason for its collapse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/06/coronavirus-and-flybe-collapse-perfect-storm-impacts-on-tourism/|title=Coronavirus and Flybe collapse: 'Perfect storm' impacts on tourism|last=Maguire|first=Jack|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, Channel Islands airline [[Blue Islands]] announced that flights between Jersey and [[London City Airport]] would be cancelled temporarily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/11/flights-cancelled-as-coronavirus-puts-travellers-off/|title=Flights cancelled as coronavirus puts travellers off|last=Stephenson|first=Lucy|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, [[Condor Ferries]] announced that the ''[[Commodore Clipper]]'' would not carry passengers for a month in order to ensure the continuity of its freight service using the ship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-13/commodore-clipper-will-not-to-carry-passengers-for-the-next-month-due-to-coronavirus/|title=No passengers to travel on Commodore Clipper for the next month due to Coronavirus|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 17 March, it announced that sailings to and from [[Saint-Malo]] would be suspended from 24 March to at least 2 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-17/condor-to-bring-passengers-home-from-st-malo-and-then-suspend-sailings/|title=Condor to bring passengers home from St Malo, and then suspend sailings|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The company subsequently announced that it would cancel all passenger sailings from 27 March until at least 30 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.condorferries.co.uk/ferry-routes-ports/plan-your-journey/sailing-updates/condor-liberation-condor-rapide-important-information-about-your-sailing-from-27th-march-to-30th-april-inclusive|title=Sailing update information|website=Condor Ferries|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> This was later extended to 14 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/04/08/covid-19-condors-passenger-ferry-suspension-extended/|title=Covid-19: Condor's passenger ferry suspension extended|last=Taylor|first=Ed|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Blue Islands announced that flights between Jersey and [[Guernsey]] would be suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-20/blue-islands-flights-to-guernsey-stop/|title=Blue islands flights to Guernsey stop|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the island's bus operator [[LibertyBus]] announced a reduced timetable from 28 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-27/bus-journeys-in-jersey-reduced-during-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=Bus journeys in Jersey reduced during coronavirus pandemic|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, [[Jersey Airport]] announced that [[British Airways]] flights between [[Gatwick Airport|Gatwick]] and Jersey will be suspended from 31 March until the end of April.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=JERairport|number=1243862756136288258|title=Due to the current situation BA Jersey/Gatwick services will be suspended as from Tuesday 31 March until end of April. Passengers due to travel during this period should contact the airline directly for alternative options.|date=2020-03-28|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, [[EasyJet]] announced that it was grounding its entire fleet until further notice. EasyJet operated several flights a day between Jersey and London Gatwick as well as to eight other regional airports such as Liverpool.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyairport.com/News/Pages/easyJet-Statement---fleet-grounding.aspx?fbclid=IwAR3cREcZ3nCmyQzWfN-1v8KFAnDfCwjgoMTUG7IjS-71_aL8Pyfw-7jpnic|title=easyJet Statement - fleet grounding|website=www.jerseyairport.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April the Jersey government announced that it was in negotiation with Blue Islands for the airline to provide continuity of air travel to the UK for passengers whose travel is deemed essential.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.je:80/News/2020/Pages/EssentialFlights.aspx|title=Essential air travel service|website=gov.je|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April it was announced that nobody would be allowed to board a Blue Island aircraft without government approval for the journey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/new-documentation-needed-fly-blue-islands-lifeline-services/#.Xp6fGxSArlI|title=Government approval now needed to fly|website=Bailiwick Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===End of Life and Funerals===\nIn March, restrictions on funerals include a ban on church services and only a maximum of ten mourners who must be immediate family may attend was implemented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-23/drastic-changes-to-funerals-in-jersey-to-prevent-spread-of-coronavirus/|title=Drastic changes to funerals in Jersey to prevent spread of Coronavirus|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\"undertakers\" />\n\nThe island has capacity for the storage of 100 bodies across the hospital and funeral homes, but the Government has plans to set up a temporary [[morgue]] called \u2018The Sanctum\u2019 if this is exceeded.<ref name=\"undertakers\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/04/08/island-well-prepared-for-worst-case-scenario-of-covid-deaths/|title=Island 'well prepared for worst-case scenario' of Covid deaths|last=Maguire|first=Jack|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn mid April, the March ban on visiting dying patients was lifted to permit relatives wearing PPE to visit their loved ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/news/family-members-allowed-visit-dying-relatives/#.Xp6n4RSArlI|title=Family members allowed to say last goodbyes|website=www.bailiwickexpress.com |language=en|access-date=2020-04-21|date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Other reactions==\nOn 19 March, the island's telecommunications operators announced a free increase in broadband speed to 1[[Data-rate units#Gigabit per second|Gb/s]] for all subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-19/free-fibre-internet-upgrade-for-jersey-during-coronavirus/|title=Free fibre internet upgrade for Jersey during Coronavirus|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, [[Rubis (company)|Rubis]] announced that it would be offering free fuel to all frontline hospital workers at hospitals across the Channel Islands. Workers will be able to claim a fuel voucher which may be used at any Rubis forecourt.<ref>{{cite news |title=Free fuel for hospital workers |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/business/free-fuel-hospital-workers/?fbclid=IwAR3VQmGfQfh_v2ahKHSZCMbVsO9nhuMnjIPLK8qyxSjoP7rivJergQ7_Sp8 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Number of cases per day===\nThe figures below count only confirmed cases from tests; the actual number of infections and cases are likely to be higher than reported.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lau |first1=Hien |last2=Khosrawipour |first2=Veria |last3=Kocbach |first3=Piotr |last4=Mikolajczyk |first4=Agata |last5=Ichii |first5=Hirohito |last6=Schubert |first6=Justyna |last7=Bania |first7=Jacek |last8=Khosrawipour |first8=Tanja |title=Internationally lost COVID-19 cases |journal=Journal of Microbiology, Immunology and Infection |date=March 2020 |doi=10.1016/j.jmii.2020.03.013|pmid=32205091 |pmc=7102572 }}</ref>\n\nLast updated 15:15 24 April 2020. Data sourced from the [https://www.gov.je/Health/Coronavirus/Pages/CoronavirusCases.aspx Government of Jersey website].\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:86%\"\n! colspan=\"9\" | March\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=70px | Date\n! colspan=\"2\" width=100px | Confirmed cases\n! colspan=\"2\" width=100px | Deaths\n! colspan=\"2\" width=100px | Negative results\n! colspan=\"2\" width=80px | Confirmed recoveries\n|-\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n|-\n\n|-\n