wn |first=Robin |last2=''The Boston Globe'' |publisher=Globe Pequot |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-7627-5062-7 |edition=First}}\n* {{Cite book |title=City in Time: Boston |last=Hantover |first=Jeffrey |last2=King |first2=Gilbert |publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Inc. |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4027-3300-0}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UY5SjKPbaGoC |title=The Hub's Metropolis: Greater Boston's Development from Railroad Suburbs to Smart Growth |last=O'Connell |first=James C. |publisher=MIT Press |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-262-01875-3}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Boston: A to Z |last=O'Connor |first=Thomas H. |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-674-00310-1}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RbMBOZux_JsC |title=Boston's Immigrants, 1840\u20131925 |last=Price |first=Michael |last2=Sammarco |first2=Anthony Mitchell |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-7524-0921-4}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Mapping Boston |publisher=MIT Press |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-262-61173-2 |editor-last=Krieger |editor-first=Alex |editor-last2=Cobb |editor-first2=David |editor-last3=Turner |editor-first3=Amy}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/gaininggroundhis0000seas |title=Gaining Ground: A History of Landmaking in Boston |last=Seasholes |first=Nancy S. |publisher=[[MIT Press]] |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-262-19494-5 |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |url-access=registration}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/builtinbostoncit00shan_0 |title=Built in Boston: City & Suburb, 1800\u20132000 |last=Shand-Tucci |first=Douglass |publisher=University of Massachusetts Press |year=1999 |isbn=978-1-55849-201-1 |edition=2}}\n* {{Cite book |title=AIA Guide to Boston, 3rd Edition: Contemporary Landmarks, Urban Design, Parks, Historic Buildings and Neighborhoods |last=Southworth |first=Michael |last2=Southworth |first2=Susan |publisher=Globe Pequot |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-7627-4337-7 |edition=3}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/wheninbostontime00jimv_0 |title=When in Boston: A Time Line & Almanac |last=Vrabel |first=Jim |last2=Bostonian Society |publisher=Northeastern University Press |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-55553-620-6 |url-access=registration}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/bostontopographi00whit_1 |title=Boston: A Topographical History |last=Whitehill |first=Walter Muir |last2=Kennedy |first2=Lawrence W. |publisher=Belknap Press of Harvard University Press |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-674-00268-5 |edition=Third}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |collapsible=collapsed |voy=Boston}}\n* {{Official website|www.cityofboston.gov}}\n* {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Boston|short=x}}\n* [https://collections.leventhalmap.org/search?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=%22Boston+%28Mass.%29--Maps%22&search_field=subject Historical Maps of Boston] from the [[Norman B. Leventhal Map Center]] at the [[Boston Public Library]]\n* {{curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Massachusetts/Localities/B/Boston}}\n\n{{BostonMA}}\n{{Boston landmarks}}\n{{Public art in Boston}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Other articles relating to Boston\n|list =\n{{Suffolk County, Massachusetts}}\n{{Greater_Boston}}\n{{Massachusetts}}\n{{Northeast Megalopolis}}\n{{New England}}\n{{Northeast US}}\n{{US state capitals}}\n{{All-American City Award Hall of Fame}}\n{{Massachusetts cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1630 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Boston| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Cities in Suffolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:County seats in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Greater Boston]]\n[[Category:Irish-American culture in Boston]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Suffolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1630]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Simtropolitan", "label": "safe", "comment": "wlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"}
{"title_page": "Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus\n| series       = South Park\n| image        =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:PeriodMeeting.gif|240px|]] -->\n| caption      = Kyle, Cartman and Kenny having their \"period\" club.\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 16\n| airdate      = December 29, 1999\n| production   = 316\n| writer       = [[Trey Parker]]<br>[[Matt Stone]]\n| director     = [[Eric Stough]]\n| guests       = \n| season_article = South Park (season 3)\n| episode_list = List of South Park episodes\n| prev         = [[Mr. Hankey's Christmas Classics]]\n| next         = [[World Wide Recorder Concert]]\n}}\n\"'''Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus'''\" is the sixteenth and penultimate episode of the [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] of the animated television series ''[[South Park]]''. It was originally broadcast on December 29, 1999. The episode's title and the theme of menstruation was inspired by the book ''[[Are You There God? It's Me, Margaret.]]''\n\n==Plot synopsis==\nAs the year 2000 is approaching, [[Cartman]] realizes [[blood]] is coming out of his [[anus]], leading him to believe he is experiencing his first [[menstrual cycle|period]] and thus commencing [[puberty]]. He makes fun of the other boys for not hitting puberty yet, unaware that his bleeding is caused by a minor [[stomach]] infection that has spread across South Park, and that it can be cured with antibiotics. [[Kenny McCormick|Kenny]] later contracts the same ailment, and [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]], not wanting to be left out, pretends he is also afflicted. The boys consequently abandon [[Stan Marsh|Stan]] and leave him out of their next mission, believing he is less mature for not having had his period.\n\nMeanwhile, the people of the world flock around [[Jesus (South Park)|Jesus']] house, excited about the new millennium and saying that, at the year 2000, Jesus' father should make an appearance. Jesus contacts his father and tells him about his potential resurgence in popularity, but [[List of minor characters on South Park#God|God]] (unseen in their conversation) refuses to show up because mankind is not ready. Jesus, wanting to still satisfy the people, books [[Rod Stewart]] to play a [[New Year's Eve]] concert in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]]; everybody decides to go, because a rumor persists that God will show up.\n\nStan, meanwhile, prays for his period, but doesn't get it, so he visits [[List of recurring South Park characters#Dr. Alphonse Mephesto and Kevin|Dr. Mephesto]] and gets a bottle of [[hormone]] pills. Using them causes Stan to grow a beard, have a deeper voice, and develop a pair of [[breast]]s, but still no \"period.\" Afterwards, Kenny suddenly bursts from inside out and dies. At the hospital, they discover the reason: Kenny had shoved a [[tampon]] up his rectum. The doctor expresses concern that \"the children are all shoving tampons up their ass because they've seen the [[Backstreet Boys]] doing it on TV or something.\"\n\nThe crowd in Las Vegas for the [[Hogmanay|New Year's]] concert is enraged upon seeing Rod Stewart (portrayed here as very old and [[urinary incontinence|incontinent]]) and they turn against Jesus. With them preparing to [[crucifixion|crucify]] him again, Stan asks Jesus why God does not answer his prayers, and Jesus explains that, if God does everything for you, then your existence has no real purpose. Jesus realizes that this was God's message: Jesus had to figure his ''own'' way to get people to follow him. And just as he realizes this, God arrives.\n\nAfter the crowd's initial shock over God's appearance (distinctly unlike [[Conceptions of God|traditional depictions of God]]), God offers the people the chance to ask one question. The crowd plans to ask the [[meaning of life]] or [[existence]], but before anyone else can ask, Stan comes up and asks why he hasn't gotten his period. God explains that boys don't get periods, and tells the truth: that Cartman and Kenny are affected by the colon infection and Kyle was lying to fit in with them. God explains to Stan that he will never get a period (because he is male), but he will hit puberty when the time is right. He then returns to [[Heaven]], saying he will answer another question in the year 4000. Stan is satisfied by this, and joyfully starts singing \"[[Auld Lang Syne]]\", but the angry crowd attacks him for wasting their chance to ask God a profoundly important question, as the credits roll.\n\n==Production notes==\nIn the DVD commentary for the episode, Trey Parker and Matt Stone said that [[Comedy Central]] wanted them to produce this episode for the new millennium as every other show was producing Y2K episodes, despite that the season had ended with the prior episode [[Mr. Hankey's Christmas Classics]]. Initially, Trey Parker intended for God to look like somewhat a mixture of a [[cat]] and a [[hippopotamus|hippo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/fans/behind/interviews.php?interview=27|title=An interview with Adrien Beard}}South Park Studios; accessed February 16, 2009.</ref>\n\nThis was the first episode to feature [[Eliza Schneider]] and [[Mona Marshall]] providing the voices for the female characters following [[Mary Kay Bergman]]'s death. Schneider would continue to voice her roles until Season 7 (replaced with [[April Stewart]]), and Marshall continues to be a part of the show's cast.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/full-episodes/s03e16-are-you-there-god-its-me-jesus Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus] Full episode at South Park Studios\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/guide/episodes/s03e16-are-you-there-god-its-me-jesus Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus] Episode guide at South Park Studios\n* {{IMDb episode|0763045}}\n* {{Tv.com episode|2461}}\n\n{{South Park episodes|3}}\n\n[[Category:1999 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:God in fiction]]\n[[Category:New Year television episodes]]\n[[Category:Portrayals of Jesus on television]]\n[[Category:South Park (season 3) episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus\n| series       = South Park\n| image        =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:PeriodMeeting.gif|240px|]] -->\n| caption      = Kyle, Cartman and Kenny having their \"period\" club.\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 16\n| airdate      = December 29, 1999\n| production   = 316\n| writer       = [[Trey Parker]]<br>[[Matt Stone]]\n| director     = [[Eric Stough]]\n| guests       = \n| season_article = South Park (season 3)\n| episode_list = List of South Park episodes\n| season_list  = \n| prev         = [[Mr. Hankey's Christmas Classics]]\n| next         = [[World Wide Recorder Concert]]\n}}\n\"'''Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus'''\" is the sixteenth and penultimate episode of the [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] of the animated television series ''[[South Park]]''. It was originally broadcast on December 29, 1999. The episode's title and the theme of menstruation was inspired by the book ''[[Are You There God? It's Me, Margaret.]]''\n\n==Plot synopsis==\nAs the year 2000 is approaching, [[Cartman]] realizes [[blood]] is coming out of his [[anus]], leading him to believe he is experiencing his first [[menstrual cycle|period]] and thus commencing [[puberty]]. He makes fun of the other boys for not hitting puberty yet, unaware that his bleeding is caused by a minor [[stomach]] infection that has spread across South Park, and that it can be cured with antibiotics. [[Kenny McCormick|Kenny]] later contracts the same ailment, and [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]], not wanting to be left out, pretends he is also afflicted. The boys consequently abandon [[Stan Marsh|Stan]] and leave him out of their next mission, believing he is less mature for not having had his period.\n\nMeanwhile, the people of the world flock around [[Jesus (South Park)|Jesus']] house, excited about the new millennium and saying that, at the year 2000, Jesus' father should make an appearance. Jesus contacts his father and tells him about his potential resurgence in popularity, but [[List of minor characters on South Park#God|God]] (unseen in their conversation) refuses to show up because mankind is not ready. Jesus, wanting to still satisfy the people, books [[Rod Stewart]] to play a [[New Year's Eve]] concert in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]]; everybody decides to go, because a rumor persists that God will show up.\n\nStan, meanwhile, prays for his period, but doesn't get it, so he visits [[List of recurring South Park characters#Dr. Alphonse Mephesto and Kevin|Dr. Mephesto]] and gets a bottle of [[hormone]] pills. Using them causes Stan to grow a beard, have a deeper voice, and develop a pair of [[breast]]s, but still no \"period.\" Afterwards, Kenny suddenly bursts from inside out and dies. At the hospital, they discover the reason: Kenny had shoved a [[tampon]] up his rectum. The doctor expresses concern that \"the children are all shoving tampons up their ass because they've seen the [[Backstreet Boys]] doing it on TV or something.\"\n\nThe crowd in Las Vegas for the [[Hogmanay|New Year's]] concert is enraged upon seeing Rod Stewart (portrayed here as very old and [[urinary incontinence|incontinent]]) and they turn against Jesus. With them preparing to [[crucifixion|crucify]] him again, Stan asks Jesus why God does not answer his prayers, and Jesus explains that, if God does everything for you, then your existence has no real purpose. Jesus realizes that this was God's message: Jesus had to figure his ''own'' way to get people to follow him. And just as he realizes this, God arrives.\n\nAfter the crowd's initial shock over God's appearance (distinctly unlike [[Conceptions of God|traditional depictions of God]]), God offers the people the chance to ask one question. The crowd plans to ask the [[meaning of life]] or [[existence]], but before anyone else can ask, Stan comes up and asks why he hasn't gotten his period. God explains that boys don't get periods, and tells the truth: that Cartman and Kenny are affected by the colon infection and Kyle was lying to fit in with them. God explains to Stan that he will never get a period (because he is male), but he will hit puberty when the time is right. He then returns to [[Heaven]], saying he will answer another question in the year 4000. Stan is satisfied by this, and joyfully starts singing \"[[Auld Lang Syne]]\", but the angry crowd attacks him for wasting their chance to ask God a profoundly important question, as the credits roll.\n\n==Production notes==\nIn the DVD commentary for the episode, Trey Parker and Matt Stone said that [[Comedy Central]] wanted them to produce this episode for the new millennium as every other show was producing Y2K episodes, despite that the season had ended with the prior episode [[Mr. Hankey's Christmas Classics]]. Initially, Trey Parker intended for God to look like somewhat a mixture of a [[cat]] and a [[hippopotamus|hippo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/fans/behind/interviews.php?interview=27|title=An interview with Adrien Beard}}South Park Studios; accessed February 16, 2009.</ref> \n\nThis was the first episode to feature [[Eliza Schneider]] and [[Mona Marshall]] providing the voices for the female characters following [[Mary Kay Bergman]]'s death. Schneider would continue to voice her roles until Season 7 (replaced with [[April Stewart]]), and Marshall continues to be a part of the show's cast.{{cn|date=May 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/full-episodes/s03e16-are-you-there-god-its-me-jesus Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus] Full episode at South Park Studios\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/guide/episodes/s03e16-are-you-there-god-its-me-jesus Are You There God? It's Me, Jesus] Episode guide at South Park Studios\n* {{IMDb episode|0763045}}\n* {{Tv.com episode|2461}}\n\n{{South Park episodes|3}}\n\n[[Category:1999 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:God in fiction]]\n[[Category:New Year television episodes]]\n[[Category:Portrayals of Jesus on television]]\n[[Category:South Park (season 3) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Gonnym", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Are_You_There_God%3F_It%27s_Me,_Jesus"}
